Self-starting non-linear PI models

George N. White III

4/20/2017

Introduction

This is an R Markdown document.

R now has “self-starting” non-linear models. Pre-built versions of the most widely used 2-parameter models are available in the base R packages. Platt et al 1977 propose using the initial slope alpha and the specific production rate, PmB at “optimal” light intensity. For two-parameter models whwere there is no “optimum”, we use PsB, the “saturation” rate.

Taken from selfStart {stats}

pos.st <- which("package:stats" == search())
mSS <- apropos("^SS..", where = TRUE, ignore.case = FALSE)
(mSS <- unname(mSS[names(mSS) == pos.st]))
##  [1] "SSasymp"     "SSasympOff"  "SSasympOrig" "SSbiexp"     "SSfol"      
##  [6] "SSfpl"       "SSgompertz"  "SSlogis"     "SSmicmen"    "SSweibull"
fSS <- sapply(mSS, get, pos = pos.st, mode = "function")
all(sapply(fSS, inherits, "selfStart"))  # -> TRUE
## [1] TRUE

PI models

Consider the following sample data:

with(PI.df, plot(P~I))

Important features of this plot are the saturation value, PsB and the slope, alphaB ot the origin.

Michaelis-Menten model

The Michaelis-Menten model Vm*x/(K+x) has a shape similar to the above plot and was used by Jasby A.D. and Platt T., 1976. Mathematical formulation of the relationship between photosynthesis and light for phytoplankton. Limnol. Oceanogr. 21:540–547. For PI applications, Vm = PsB and `alphaB = PsB/K’

getInitial(P ~ SSmicmen(I, PsB, K), data = PI.df)
##       PsB         K 
##  3.275932 89.152728
MM.nls <- nls(P ~ SSmicmen(I, PsB, K), data = PI.df)

Platt et al 1980 using SSasympOrig

Platt et al 1980 adopted a different model to account for observations in which the P decreases at high I values.

   PB = PsB*(1 - exp(-alphaB*I/PsB))*exp(-betaB*I/PsB)

When the parameter betaB in this model is zero, it reduces to the following standard self-starting model:

SSasympOrig = function(x, Asym, lrc) = Asym*(1 -exp(-exp(lrc)*x)) where Asym is the asymptotic value, , and lrc is natural log of the rate constant, rc.

For P–I models, Asym = PsB, the saturation rate, and rc = alphaB/PsB. We can define SSProduction using SSasympOrig as shown below. Using the parameter estimates from the Micaelis-Menton model, however, produces a poor fit.

SSProduction <- function(Irradiance, alphaB, PsB)
{ SSasympOrig(Irradiance, PsB, log(alphaB/PsB))}
PsB <- c.MM["PsB"]
alphaB <- c.MM["alphaB"]
with(PI.df, {
               plot(I, P, ylim=c(0, PsB))
               lines(I, SSProduction(I, alphaB, PsB), col='blue')
               lines(I, SSmicmen(I, c.MM["PsB"], c.MM["K"]), col='red')
            })

Next, we estimate the parameters using SSasympOrig. Note that both PmB and alphaB are smaller than for the Michaelis-Menton model.

lrc <- log(alphaB/PsB)
(getInitial(P ~ SSasympOrig(I, PsB, lrc), data = PI.df))
##       PsB       lrc 
##  2.635119 -4.441478
asymp.nls <- nls(P ~ SSasympOrig(I, PsB, lrc), data = PI.df)

Weibull

The Weibull function adds a third parameter, pwr to the asymptotic model, giving:

    y = Asym-Drop*exp(-exp(lrc)*x^pwr

The zero-intercept constraint requiresDrop=Asym.

lrc <- log(alphaB/PsB)
pwr <- 1
Drop = PsB
(getInitial(P ~ SSweibull(I, PsB, Drop, lrc, pwr), data = PI.df))
##       PsB      Drop       lrc       pwr 
##  2.558808  2.617449 -4.941978  1.146789
weibull.nls <- nls(P ~ SSweibull(I, PsB, Drop, lrc, pwr), data = PI.df)
weibull.nls

Note that the estimated values for Asym and Drop are close, while the estimated value for pwr is close to unity. This indicates that the simpler SSasympOrig model (green line in the above plot) is preferable.

Model with photoinhibition

Next we consider the model:

PB = PsB*(1 - exp(-alphaB*I/PsB))*exp(-betaB*I/PsB)

where betaB is allowed to vary. We will use log-transformed values, lrca=log(alphaB/PsB) and lrcb=log(betaB/PsB).

We generate a test data set PI2.df:

PI2.df <- PI.df
PI2.df$P <- with(PI.df, P*exp(-0.001*I))
PIfun <- function(x, PsB, lrca, lrcb) {PsB*(1-exp(-exp(lrca)*x))*exp(-exp(lrcb)*x)}  
PsB <- c.MM["PsB"]
alphaB <- c.MM["alphaB"]
lrca <- log(alphaB/PsB)
lrcb <-  log(0.001)
with(PI2.df, {
               plot(I, P, ylim=c(0, PsB))
               lines(I, SSProduction(I, alphaB, PsB), col='blue')
               lines(I, PIfun(I, PsB, lrca, lrcb), col='red')
            })

PI2.nls <- nls(P ~ PsB*(1-exp(-exp(lrca)*I))*exp(-exp(lrcb)*I), data = PI2.df, start=list(PsB=PsB, lrca=lrca, lrcb=lrcb), trace=TRUE)

Residuals

Both models appear, at first glance, to give reasonable fits to the data. It is, however, import to examine the fits carefully. The nls objects provide residuals:

with(PI.df, matplot(I, cbind(residuals(MM.nls), residuals(asymp.nls), residuals(weibull.nls)), ylab='residual'))

The largest residuals are all associated with the Michaelis-Menton model (1). Note that the residuals for this model are negative for small and large values of I. This suggests that the asymptotic model (2) is more appropriate for this data set. Residuals for 4-parameter Weibull (3) are similar to the aymptotic model (2), confirming that there is little benefit to the added complexity.

Discussion

When there is no underlying justification for a particular model, it is useful to compare fits from several models. A model with additional parameters can be useful in confirming the results from a simpler model. For PI curves, the ultimate goal is to reduce a complicated data set to a consistent set of parameters to be used in numerical calculations.

It is also important to note that even in cases where the parameters have simple geometric interpretation (such as a slope at the origin or height of the asymptote) , estimated values for parameters should not be used with models other than the one used to generate the estimates.
